45. nemo dexterius fortuna est usus, ‘ no one ever dealt more adroitly with Fortune,' or ‘no one ever employed his high position more happily ’ than Maecenas. Horace seems to mean that Maecenas is not carried away by his high position, but that he soberly and discreetly chooses his friends, not ready to listen to every flatterer.
